rleden","1314":"1314","1336":"1336","about 1338":"circa 1338","1389":"1389","1440":"1440","1340":"1340","1362":"1362","1361":"1361","1383":"1383","1318":"1318","Reedham, Norfolk, England":"Reedham, Norfolk, England"},"en":{"1340–1361":"1340–1361","1336–1389":"1336–1389","1362–1440":"1362–1440","1314–1383":"1314–1383","1318–Female":"1318–Deceased","1314":"1314","1336":"1336","about 1338":"about 1338","1389":"1389","1440":"1440","1340":"1340","1362":"1362","1361":"1361","1383":"1383","1318":"1318","Reedham, Norfolk, England":"Reedham, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Reedham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places so named, such as High Needham in Hartington (Derbyshire), Needham in Elm (Cambridgeshire), Needham (Norfolk), Needham in Yaxley, Needham Street in Gazeley or Needham Market (all in Suffolk). These places are named with Old English <i>nēd</i> ‘need, hardship’ + <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’, denoting a place that provided a poor living.","Irish (County Mayo): Anglicized form of <b>Ó Niadh</b>, see   Nee  .","History: English explorer James Needham carried the name to the southern Carolina settlement, arriving from Barbados in 1670 as a young man."],"variants":[{"name":"Nee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, John Patrick.","Irish (Galway): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Niadh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Nia</i>’ or <b>Mac Niadh</b> ‘son of <i>Nia</i>’. Compare   McNee  .   Needham   2 and   Neville   have also been adopted as Anglicized forms of this name.","North German: possibly a relationship name from Middle Low German <i>neve</i> ‘nephew, grand-child’."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Reedham was born in 1340, in Reedham, Norfolk, England, her father, William de Reedham, was 27 and her mother, Margaret De Caston, was 23. She had at least 1 son with Sir Thomas Berney. She died in 1361, in her hometown, at the age of 21, and was buried in Reedham, Norfolk, England."},"et":{"1340–1361":"1340–1361","1336–1389":"1336–1389","1362–1440":"1362–1440","1314–1383":"1314–1383","1318–Female":"1318–Surnud","1314":"1314","1336":"1336","about 1338":"umbes 1338","1389":"1389","1440":"1440","1340":"1340","1362":"1362","1361":"1361","1383":"1383","1318":"1318","Reedham, Norfolk, England":"Reedham, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"1340–1361":"1340–1361","1336–1389":"1336–1389","1362–1440":"1362–1440","1314–1383":"1314–1383","1318–Female":"1318–Kuollut","1314":"1314","1336":"1336","about 1338":"noin 1338","1389":"1389","1440":"1440","1340":"1340","1362":"1362","1361":"1361","1383":"1383","1318":"1318","Reedham, Norfolk, England":"Reedham, Norfolk, England"},"fr":{"1340–1361":"1340–1361","1336–1389":"1336–1389","1362–1440":"1362–1440","1314–1383":"1314–1383","1318–Female":"1318–Décédée","1314":"1314","1336":"1336","about 1338":"environ 1338","1389":"1389","1440":"1440","1340":"1340","1362":"1362","1361":"1361","1383":"1383","1318":"1318","Reedham, Norfolk, England":"Reedham, Norfolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Margaret de Reedham est née en 1340, à Reedham, Norfolk, Angleterre, son père, William de Reedham, avait 27 ans et sa mère, Margaret De Caston, avait 23 ans. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Sir Thomas Berney. Elle est décédée en 1361, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 21 ans, et a été enterrée à Reedham, Norfolk, Angleterre."},"de":{"1340–1361":"1340–1361","1336–1389":"1336–1389","1362–1440":"1362–1440","13